<Base title="About — Ming Ma" description="Ming Ma's background: 15 years building products at Facebook, ByteDance, Scroll, Tranchess and more.">
  <h1>About</h1>

  <p>
    I started as an engineer, became a data scientist, then stumbled into product management and never looked back.
  </p>

  <p>
    Big tech gave me the playbook. Startups taught me when to ignore it.
  </p>

  <p>
    At <a href="https://tranchess.com" target="_blank">Tranchess</a> I helped steward a DeFi protocol through a $1.8B TVL peak and a full bear market — and came out the other side.
    At <a href="https://scroll.io" target="_blank">Scroll</a> I parachuted in to run the mainnet launch, then built the product team from scratch.
    We shipped <a href="https://scroll.io/blog/scroll-canvas-build-your-onchain-story" target="_blank" title="Scroll Canvas — an onchain identity and reputation layer on Ethereum">Canvas</a> (an onchain identity layer) and Origin NFT — nearly a million NFTs minted.
  </p>

  <p>
    Now I'm in the middle of an honest FOMO about AI. Not the hype kind — the kind where you start using these tools every day and realize the rules are changing again.
    I'm running experiments: how do you actually manage a team with AI? What does it do to how products get built? Where's the startup idea that only makes sense now?
  </p>

  <p>
    I'm open to interesting problems. If you're building something that fits — or just want to think out loud —
    <a href="mailto:mamingming@gmail.com">reach out</a>.
  </p>

